Project Overview¶
For this project, the group is Mohini Yadav and Erin Nell.


We will be conducting an analysis on the Spotify streaming data for 2023 and 2024. The dataset, Spotify Songs Streamed 2023, includes various features such as song titles, artists, and release years, and streaming counts across different platforms for the year of 2023. The Spotify Songs Streamed 2024 dataset includes the same variables, but with some added information about a songs performance on social media platforms, such as TikTok or YouTube.


We believe that working with Spotify streaming data presents a unique opportunity to further understand market insights and song performance. Analyzing streaming data helps us understand current music trends, and evolving listener preferences. This insight can be valuable for artists, producers, and marketers in the music industry. With song performance, understanding which songs perform best on streaming platforms can inform marketing strategies and decisions on which songs to promote.


Some possible questions for further exploration are: Can we use the Spotify Stream count across the years to understand what songs remain the most streamed songs over the years. Moreover, does social media like TikTok play a roll in how much a song is streamed? Do characteristics such as acousticness, energy, or explicitness affect stream count?






















Collaboration Plan¶
The team plans to meet once a week to work on and discuss the project and determine next steps. We will also communicate frequently over text messages to stay updated with our progress on the project and, if necessary, we will meet over facetime or schedule additional in-person meetings. We also have a Google Doc which has a list of to-do items and general notes about the project. Lastly, we have a shared Github repository where we may store and update our code.






















Extraction, Transform, and Load¶
We first begin by loading a dataset from Kaggle which contains the Spotify streaming data for 2023. We tidy the data by removing unwanted columns, such as the the cover_url link which we would not be using in our analysis, ensuring the data is the correct type, and replacing cells incomplete data with NaN values or deleting the row depending on the context.

df_tidy2024 = df2024

# dropping columns not useful to our analysis

                                'Pandora Track Stations', 'Soundcloud Streams', 'Shazam Counts', 'TIDAL Popularity',
                                 'Apple Music Playlist Count', 'Deezer Playlist Count',
                                'Apple Music Playlist Count', 'YouTube Playlist Reach', 'ISRC'], axis=1)

columns_to_clean = [
    'Spotify Streams', 'YouTube Views', 'YouTube Likes',
    'TikTok Posts', 'TikTok Likes', 'TikTok Views',  'AirPlay Spins']
for column in columns_to_clean:
    df_tidy2024[column] = df_tidy2024[column].str.replace(',', '', regex=False)

In [36]:






df2023 = df
df2024 = df_tidy2024

# standardizing the column names for when we merge
df2023.rename(columns={'track_name': 'song', 'artist(s)_name': 'artist'}, inplace=True)
df2024.rename(columns={'Track': 'song', 'Artist': 'artist'}, inplace=True)

# merging the the dataframes based on an inner join so we only get songs that appear both in 2023 and 2024
merged_dfs = pd.merge(df2023, df2024, on=['song', 'artist'], how='inner')

# dropping columns we dont need
merged_dfs = merged_dfs.drop(columns=['Release Date', 'Album Name', 'All Time Rank', 'in_spotify_charts', 'Spotify Popularity', 'Track Score'])

# renaming based on year
merged_dfs.rename(columns={'streams': 'streams_2023', 'Spotify Streams': 'streams_2024'}, inplace=True)

# add new column which shows the difference between the stream count by year
merged_dfs['stream_change'] = merged_dfs['streams_2024'] - merged_dfs['streams_2023']

# remove songs with a negative stream change since that is impossible and means the stream count was entered in incorrectly
merged_dfs = merged_dfs[merged_dfs['stream_change'] >= 0]

# creating a new column order so (spotify) streams are next to each other
new_column_order = ['song', 'artist', 'artist_count', 'released_year', 'released_month',
       'released_day', 'streams_2023', 'streams_2024', 'stream_change','bpm', 'key', 'mode', 'danceability_%', 'valence_%',
        'energy_%', 'acousticness_%', 'instrumentalness_%', 'liveness_%', 'speechiness_%', 'YouTube Views',
        'YouTube Likes', 'TikTok Posts', 'TikTok Likes', 'TikTok Views', 'AirPlay Spins', 'Explicit Track']
merged_dfs = merged_dfs[new_column_order]

# if there are duplicates, so keep first occurence of the duplicate
merged_dfs = merged_dfs[~merged_dfs['song'].duplicated(keep='first')]

merged_dfs.head()

From our summary statistics, we can see that on average, songs for example, have an energy of 65% and TikTok likes of 218,677,600. This can help us begin to draw conclusions, such as songs are more likely to be successful (and make this list) if they have a high percentage of energy or over 200,000,000 likes on TikTok.






















Next, we wanted to look into some of the additional attributes included in this dataset, such as the percentage of the song that is acoustic. From the summary statistics below we can infer that songs with less acousticness are more likely to appear on this list of most streamed songs. This is evident from the average being about 27% acousticness and 75% of the data falling beneath an acoustic level of 43%. In contrast, energy has a average percentage of 63, with the third quartil being at 77%. Thus, songs with a relatively high energy level, at least higher than acousticness, are going to appear on this list.

Bar Chart


Another useful analysis we can make is finding a bar chart which looks at the songs which continued to grow in streams from 2023 and 2024. From this graph, we can help identify the songs that had a sustained popularity which we can later perform further analysis on to discover why these songs remained popular. Moreover, we can compare this to the top 10 songs with the largest increase in streams and perform further analysis to figure out what about these songs made them only perform well for a short period of time.

Boxplot


We can also create a boxplot to see if there is any correlation between a songs change in streams from 2023 to 2024 and if the track is explicit:


















In [44]:






import seaborn as sns

# plot a boxplot that measures the stream change to whether or not the track is explicit
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
sns.boxplot(x='Explicit Track', y='stream_change', data=merged_dfs)
plt.title("Boxplot of Stream Change by Explicit Track")
plt.xlabel('Explicit Track (False = No, True = Yes)')
plt.ylabel('Stream Change (2023 to 2024)')
plt.show()
















































We can see that the average of non-explicit songs is a bit higher than that of explicit songs. Moreover, non-explicit songs also have a larger inter-quartile-range. However, this means that just because a song is explicit, is can perform just as well over time as songs without explicit lyrics as their means are similar and have outliers in a similar range. Despite this, a song with no explicit content is likely to perform better.






















Heat Map


A heatmap is going to be a good way to quickly gauge the correlation between different variables. We can see on our map that there is a relatively strong correlation between YouTube Views, Youtube Likes, and Airplay Spins with the streams by year. This holds for when looking at the stream change variable (which shows which songs continued to have a lot of streams from 2023 and 2024), but interestingly the Airplay Spins has the highest correlation. This means that there is a correlation between how often a song is played on the radio and its total streams.

Scatter Plots


To get an idea about how the stream count for each year is related to the energy percentage, a scatter plot can be used. Below, we see that the plots look relatively similar across the two years, and that songs with energy above 20% make the list of top streamed songs for both years. As for if there are other patterns, there appears to be a relatively even spread of the data from about 25% to songs near 100% energy. In other words, songs with 25% energy versus above 90% energy have performed just as well.

Although this is not currently one of the characteristics of the data we are going to set our models on, it could potentially be used and otherwise provides an interesting insight on when music is released.

Building Models¶
We are planning to build models to understand the impact of social media on streaming popularity and the effect of song characteristics on stream count:


Model 1:


Question: Does social media like TikTok and YouTube play a role in how much a song is streamed?


Approach: For this, we plan to use a K-nearest neighbors (KNN) model. KNN will analyze songs based on their social media activity and identify patterns. By comparing the social media activity of songs in the same cluster, we can find whether higher social media engagement is related to higher streaming counts or changes in streams.


Dependent Variable: the change in stream count from 2023 to 2024, stream_change


Independent Variables: TikTok metrics (TikTok Likes, TikTok Views) YouTube Likes and potentially AirPlay Spins.


Model 2:


Question: Do characteristics such as acousticness, energy, or explicitness affect stream count?


Approach: We plan to compare two logistic regression models to determine whether characteristics like acousticness_%, energy_%, and Explicit Track are significant predictors of a song achieving high stream counts. We will model the likelihood that a song has a high stream change based on these characteristics.


Dependent Variable: the stream count, either streams_2024 or streams_2023.


Independent variables: include song characteristics (acousticness_%, energy_%, Explicit Track).
